entry.title: Revert "ozone/drm: Leave Link Status=Bad when a Connector Has no Modes"
entry.content:
This reverts commit a3bb1cf7641c234901a8385c4b1fcf91c493dd5c.



Reason for revert:

Querying all connectors for each modeset test and modeset introduces

a significant delay to the display configuration process, especially

during display configuration fallback in Chrome.



Revert and try to find a solution that doesn't require connector

fetching from DRM.



Original change's description:

> ozone/drm: Leave Link Status=Bad when a Connector Has no Modes

>

> Currently, Chrome always resets a connector's link status to GOOD before

> modesetting. This is important when a connector is reported by DRM to

> have some operational bandwidth and modes, since a connector that was

> previously marked in a bad state must be reset in order to successfully

> atomic commit in the future.

>

> However, if link-training fallback attempts have exhausted all possible

> bit-rate combinations and still failed to train the connector, it should

> have all its modes pruned and marked in a bad state.

>

> Chrome already prunes all connectors that are marked connected and have

> no modes [1]. This ensures that connectors that are in a bad state are

> ignored by higher layers of Chrome (e.g. Ash/Lacros) and no modeset or

> page flips are attempted on them (simply because a display abstraction

> will not not exists for the pruned connector).

>

> This patch ensures that the connectors that are ignored by Chrome are

> also left in a bad state when the other connectors are being modeset.

>

> [1] https://source.chromium.org/chromium/chromium/src/+/main:ui/ozone/platform/drm/common/drm_util.cc;l=415-418

entry.title: LoAF: support approximate source locations for promise resolvers
entry.content:
Attribute the source location of a promise resolver that contributed

to LoAF to the script that created it, e.g. the script that called

fetch().



Getting the exact source location of the promise resolver itself

would require capturing a stack trace, which might be too much

overhead, so this is the next best thing. We can revise in the future

whether a shallow stack trace is something we're OK with in some

circumstances.



Note that it's impossible to get the location of the actual then(),

as that's a microtask that's batched together with all the rest of

the microtasks (e.g. other then()s of the same promise).



The animation frame monitor maintains a weak map between the promise

resolver and the source location of the event

listener/script-block/callback that was responsible for creating it.

This source location is then used when a promise is resolved and the

resolution task is a long script that contributes to the LoAF.

> a scaled canvas.

entry.title: Set FormFieldData::is_autofilled only on fills
entry.content:
Autofill used to set FormFieldData::is_autofilled whenever the

WebAutofillState was either kAutofilled or kPreviewed. This made the

browser not able to distinguish filled from previewed fields.



This issue causes problems in suggetions when they are triggered while

hovering over a previous suggestion (see linked bug for more details).

And even the the filling-after-broken-suggestions was also broken.



This CL fixes the issue by setting the boolean only for

WebAutofilState::kAutofilled. Note that now the browser cannot

distinguish between previewed and not filled fields, but that should

not be a problem.

entry.title: webview(metrics): Fix host package information in SDK runtime
entry.content:
The context we retrieve for the SDK runtime is a generic

sdksandbox context. This results in our metrics and minidumps

reporting a generic package name that won't help

for investigating issues.



The good news is that the uid for the SDK sandbox

process does belong to the host app and there is a deterministic

relationship between the SDK process and the host app

so we can get the host apps information from it.



The one tricky bit is that this trick doesn't apply to the

render process because it is an isolated process and so

doesn't have this same relationship.

We settled on feeding this through as a command line

switch.



I unfortunately haven't added tests because we don't

have any instrumentation tests for the SDK runtime

and this behavior is wildly environment specific.

I just tested it manually with a shell app that contains

a WebView and also confirmed that the mini dumps show

correctly in the dev UI when I induce a crash with

chrome://crash. I have also tested this against staging

crashpad and confirmed that the crashes show up there.
